1
00:00:16,503 --> 00:00:19,503
I was in my laboratory...

2
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:22,840
probably talking to students.

3
00:00:26,079 --> 00:00:28,681
Here's a call, comes out of the blue.

4
00:00:28,682 --> 00:00:29,749
This young guy...

5
00:00:29,750 --> 00:00:32,750
wanted to know ifthe technology
was ready to be commercialized.

6
00:00:35,489 --> 00:00:38,090
Then he said the magic word.
He says'

7
00:00:38,091 --> 00:00:41,091
"I have access to some money
that would allow us to get started."

8
00:00:42,295 --> 00:00:45,295
And I said, "Okay."

9
00:00:45,532 --> 00:00:48,532
I said,
"Where does the money originate?"
And he said,

10
00:00:49,536 --> 00:00:52,536
"I'm a junior member
at a venture capital firm."

11
00:00:56,943 --> 00:00:59,779
I went to look up what
"venture capital" meant.

12
00:00:59,780 --> 00:01:02,548
I had never heard ofit before.

13
00:01:07,587 --> 00:01:09,622
The risks were just enormous.

14
00:01:09,623 --> 00:01:11,390
They came to me
with no business plan.

15
00:01:11,391 --> 00:01:13,793
Willing to risk everything
You have to be a street fighter.

16
00:01:13,794 --> 00:01:16,128
Tick, tick, tick, tick, tick.
We didn't know what
we were doing.

17
00:01:16,129 --> 00:01:17,997
Silicon Valley.
Technical breakthrough.

18
00:01:17,998 --> 00:01:19,298
$100000.
A million dollars.

19
00:01:19,299 --> 00:01:20,866
$10billion.
Intel.

20
00:01:20,867 --> 00:01:22,168
Apple.
Genentech.

21
00:01:22,169 --> 00:01:23,235
Cisco.
Good markets.

22
00:01:23,236 --> 00:01:24,637
Create companies.
Growing companies.

23
00:01:24,638 --> 00:01:27,638
The sky's the limit.
The rest is history.

24
00:01:28,675 --> 00:01:31,675
I don't know to write a business plan.
I can only tell you how weread them.

25
00:01:32,779 --> 00:01:34,680
And we start at the back.

26
00:01:34,681 --> 00:01:37,681
And ifthe numbers are big,
we look at the front to see
what kind ofbusiness it is.

27
00:01:43,356 --> 00:01:46,356
You have to look at the way
conventional wisdom works
and abandon it.

28
00:01:51,698 --> 00:01:54,698
No one
has ever accused me
ofunderestimating...

29
00:01:55,001 --> 00:01:58,001
myself.

30
00:02:02,375 --> 00:02:05,375
Jobs and Wozniak came up to see me.

31
00:02:06,713 --> 00:02:09,713
Steve Jobs is a national treasure.

32
00:02:10,050 --> 00:02:13,050
He is so visionary and so bright.

33
00:02:14,154 --> 00:02:17,154
Uh, I had to fire him though.

34
00:02:23,830 --> 00:02:26,830
These men didn't always wield
such influence and power.

35
00:02:28,335 --> 00:02:31,335
In the beginning, they barely
knew what they were doing.

36
00:02:32,172 --> 00:02:35,172
Fifty years ago, they were just
young guys from modest means...

37
00:02:36,243 --> 00:02:39,243
who thought they could
help build innovative companies.

38
00:02:40,180 --> 00:02:42,681
This is the story ofa handful ofmen...

39
00:02:42,682 --> 00:02:45,682
who stirred up a revolution
in finance and technology,

40
00:02:46,353 --> 00:02:49,353
because they saw opportunity
where others only saw risk.

41
00:03:14,314 --> 00:03:16,882
Venture capital.

42
00:03:16,883 --> 00:03:19,883
I don't think I thought ofit first.

43
00:03:23,657 --> 00:03:25,090
But I don't know
anyone...

44
00:03:25,091 --> 00:03:28,091
who used the term before I did.

45
00:03:34,501 --> 00:03:36,835
Back in the spring of1957,

46
00:03:36,836 --> 00:03:39,836
Arthur Rock was just
a junior banker on Wall Street.

47
00:03:40,507 --> 00:03:43,507
But then one day, an unsolicited letter
arrived at the office.

48
00:03:45,145 --> 00:03:48,145
The letter was unusual,
and no one else at his brokerage firm
knew what to do with it.

49
00:03:50,383 --> 00:03:52,184
It was a cry for help.

50
00:03:52,185 --> 00:03:55,185
And it would forever change
the trajectory ofArthur Rock's life.

51
00:03:57,157 --> 00:03:59,592
You gotta be lucky.

52
00:03:59,593 --> 00:04:02,593
Everybody's gonna be lucky
at some time or another.

53
00:04:02,596 --> 00:04:05,596
Thing I'd say is,
I was lucky to be lucky early.

54
00:04:08,702 --> 00:04:10,869
The letter on Arthur Rock's desk...

55
00:04:10,870 --> 00:04:13,839
had come from eight engineers
in California.

56
00:04:15,475 --> 00:04:17,476
A group ofbrilliant young men...

57
00:04:17,477 --> 00:04:20,477
who would soon become known
as "the Traitorous Eight."

58
00:04:22,816 --> 00:04:25,784
We were young guys.

59
00:04:25,785 --> 00:04:28,785
A bunch ofyoung engineers
and scientists mostly...

60
00:04:31,291 --> 00:04:34,291
working together
at Shockley Semiconductor.

61
00:04:36,496 --> 00:04:39,496
They were having a hard time with
Shockley, and they were gonna leave.

62
00:04:41,501 --> 00:04:44,501
Things had deteriorated
at Shockley Lab.

63
00:04:45,005 --> 00:04:48,005
He was a very difficult person
to work with.

64
00:04:48,408 --> 00:04:51,408
And a group ofus started considering
the possibility at least ofleaving.

65
00:04:53,513 --> 00:04:56,015
So anyhow, we did write-

66
00:04:56,016 --> 00:04:59,016
"'This prospectus is to introduce
a group ofsenior scientists
and engineers...

67
00:05:02,422 --> 00:05:05,422
who have been working
together at the Shockley
Semiconductor Laboratory."

68
00:05:07,894 --> 00:05:10,262
Shockley had just won a Nobel Prize.

69
00:05:10,263 --> 00:05:13,263
It was probably a little presumptuous
ofus to think we could push him aside.

70
00:05:14,668 --> 00:05:17,668
"A group feeling arose
to the effect...

71
00:05:17,971 --> 00:05:20,739
that rather than leave one by one,

72
00:05:20,740 --> 00:05:23,740
we believe that we are much more
valuable to an employer as a group."

73
00:05:31,651 --> 00:05:34,651
These were, by their résumés,
very superior people,

74
00:05:35,955 --> 00:05:38,724
and I thought, "Gee, maybe
there's something here."

75
00:05:38,725 --> 00:05:41,725
Something more valuable
than just to be an employee.

76
00:05:44,331 --> 00:05:46,065
That "something" that Arthur saw...

77
00:05:46,066 --> 00:05:49,066
inspired him to step out ofhis
ordinary role as a Wall Street banker.

78
00:05:51,237 --> 00:05:54,237
And that's when we met
Arthur Rock.

79
00:05:55,008 --> 00:05:58,008
Arthur came out to meet
with the group ofus.

80
00:05:58,812 --> 00:06:01,812
And Arthur said, "You ought to
start your own company,
and we'll find financing for you."

81
00:06:04,784 --> 00:06:07,486
They hadn't thought
ofthis idea themselves.

82
00:06:07,487 --> 00:06:10,487
Nobody thought ofstarting
their own company in those days.

83
00:06:10,657 --> 00:06:12,658
It was a new idea,
but it was a good one.

84
00:06:12,659 --> 00:06:15,659
At that time, there was
no venture capital,

85
00:06:16,129 --> 00:06:18,030
so starting companies was new.

86
00:06:18,031 --> 00:06:20,032
It was innovative.

87
00:06:20,033 --> 00:06:23,033
Arthur Rock had to
get creative about finding capital
for the Traitorous Eight.

88
00:06:24,804 --> 00:06:27,804
His bank had contacts with
rich families like the Rockefellers
and the Whitneys,

89
00:06:29,509 --> 00:06:32,509
but they weren't interested
in backing a start-up
all the way out in California.

90
00:06:34,981 --> 00:06:37,981
So we, uh, made a list
ofcompanies.

91
00:06:40,987 --> 00:06:42,888
In fact we sat down with
the Wall Street Journal-

92
00:06:42,889 --> 00:06:45,889
Looking for companies to ask
to invest in these eight fellas
in forming a new company.

93
00:06:50,630 --> 00:06:53,630
I think we had 35 companies.

94
00:06:54,167 --> 00:06:57,167
All of them said no. "No!"

95
00:07:04,344 --> 00:07:06,078
The attempt
to start a new company...

96
00:07:06,079 --> 00:07:07,713
might have ended
then and there,

97
00:07:07,714 --> 00:07:10,182
with the Traitorous Eight
returning to their job search...

98
00:07:10,183 --> 00:07:13,118
and Arthur Rock admitting defeat.

99
00:07:13,119 --> 00:07:16,119
But then Arthur received
one last lead.

100
00:07:16,856 --> 00:07:19,856
We were pretty much at wits, end.

101
00:07:20,126 --> 00:07:23,126
And somebody suggested
that I see Sherman Fairchild.

102
00:07:25,565 --> 00:07:28,565
Sherman Fairchild was
an entrepreneur himself...

103
00:07:28,935 --> 00:07:31,935
and also a very wealthy man.

104
00:07:32,572 --> 00:07:35,572
He right away saw the possibilities,

105
00:07:36,476 --> 00:07:39,476
and decided that Fairchild
Camera and Instrument...

106
00:07:40,580 --> 00:07:43,580
would invest the million and a half
dollars we were looking for.

107
00:07:45,351 --> 00:07:48,351
I call myself
"the accidental entrepreneur."

108
00:07:50,824 --> 00:07:53,158
With the 1.5 million Arthur raised,

109
00:07:53,159 --> 00:07:56,159
the Traitorous Eight started
Fairchild Semiconductor
in Mountain View, California,

110
00:07:58,097 --> 00:08:01,097
a sleepy rural town
35 miles south ofSan Francisco.

111
00:08:04,437 --> 00:08:07,437
Fairchild was the first company
to manufacture...

112
00:08:07,474 --> 00:08:10,474
the sophisticated silicon chips
that would power computers,

113
00:08:10,877 --> 00:08:13,877
rockets and spacecraft,

114
00:08:14,113 --> 00:08:17,113
paving the way
for the high-tech age.

115
00:08:19,152 --> 00:08:21,987
In time, the fruit orchards
surrounding Fairchild...

116
00:08:21,988 --> 00:08:24,790
would give way
to electronics companies,

117
00:08:24,791 --> 00:08:27,791
and the area would become famous
as the Silicon Valley.

118
00:08:30,163 --> 00:08:33,163
Ifthey hadn't
stayed together and formed
Fairchild Semiconductor,

119
00:08:33,700 --> 00:08:36,700
probably there'd be
no silicon in Silicon Valley.

120
00:08:39,706 --> 00:08:42,706
♪♪

121
00:08:45,445 --> 00:08:48,445
Arthur Rock
had gotten a taste ofsomething
exciting and significant.

122
00:08:49,449 --> 00:08:51,583
But as it tu ns out,
he wasn't the only one...

123
00:08:51,584 --> 00:08:54,584
trying to figgure out
how to fund young companies.

124
00:08:54,654 --> 00:08:57,556
Just up the road from Fairchild,
a handful ofbusinessmen...

125
00:08:57,557 --> 00:09:00,557
were experimenting with their own
version ofventure capital...

126
00:09:01,060 --> 00:09:04,060
together, around a lunch table
in San Francisco.

127
00:09:04,597 --> 00:09:07,597
♪ The best things in life
are free ♪

128
00:09:07,967 --> 00:09:10,736
♪ But you can give them
to the birds and bees ♪

129
00:09:10,737 --> 00:09:13,205
♪ I need money ♪

130
00:09:13,206 --> 00:09:15,440
In the '50s and '60s,

131
00:09:15,441 --> 00:09:18,410
there were a group ofus
in San Francisco
that used to get interested...

132
00:09:18,411 --> 00:09:21,411
in small, high-tech companies
down the peninsula.

133
00:09:21,748 --> 00:09:24,683
There were, I think, five ofus
in our group.

134
00:09:24,684 --> 00:09:27,684
We all had jobs, but we had
other time on our hands too,

135
00:09:28,888 --> 00:09:31,888
and we decided we just would put
a little investment club together.

136
00:09:32,058 --> 00:09:34,293
We were just a bunch of
young men in San Francisco...

137
00:09:34,294 --> 00:09:36,194
who knew each other
and respected each other.

138
00:09:36,195 --> 00:09:39,195
What it was like was
a very close fraternity.

139
00:09:39,465 --> 00:09:41,800
I guess I can use
that word carefully.

140
00:09:41,801 --> 00:09:44,636
We'd have a table
ofsix or eight for lunch.

141
00:09:44,637 --> 00:09:47,637
None ofus had enough money
to do an investment by ourselves,
so we had to have help.

142
00:09:51,244 --> 00:09:53,946
Ifone ofus ran across
an entrepreneur...

143
00:09:53,947 --> 00:09:56,947
who was trying to start a company,
we would invite him up for lunch.

144
00:09:57,050 --> 00:10:00,050
And after lunch, we would
ask him to step out onto
the street corner for a while.

145
00:10:02,221 --> 00:10:04,990
Give us 10 minutes,
and we would make up our mind
as to whether we wanted...

146
00:10:04,991 --> 00:10:07,492
to invest in his company or not.

147
00:10:07,493 --> 00:10:09,027
I don't remember that.

148
00:10:09,028 --> 00:10:10,596
We didn't do that.

149
00:10:10,597 --> 00:10:12,331
We were too classy to do that.

150
00:10:12,332 --> 00:10:14,132
That's a little bit quick, I think.

151
00:10:14,133 --> 00:10:17,133
Ifthe guy's a real nut'
why, you'd say good-bye to him...

152
00:10:17,337 --> 00:10:20,337
without asking him
to go get a cup ofcoffee.

153
00:10:21,808 --> 00:10:24,276
Two members of the group
wanted to do even more...

154
00:10:24,277 --> 00:10:27,277
than gather around
a lunch table every six weeks.

155
00:10:27,580 --> 00:10:30,580
In 1962,
Pitch Johnson and Bill Draper...

156
00:10:31,184 --> 00:10:33,952
put up all their personal savings,
quit their day jobs...

157
00:10:33,953 --> 00:10:36,953
to form a partnership,
and hit the streets.

158
00:10:37,023 --> 00:10:40,023
Pitch and I each got a Pontiac leased,

159
00:10:40,193 --> 00:10:43,193
and went around
and knocked on doors.

160
00:10:44,063 --> 00:10:47,063
And ifit sounded
like ABC Electronics,

161
00:10:48,635 --> 00:10:51,635
then we'd go in, ask the president
to sit down and tell us,
"What do you do?"

162
00:10:52,238 --> 00:10:53,905
You know.
"Well, what do you do?"

163
00:10:53,906 --> 00:10:55,841
"Well, venture capital."
"What's that?"

164
00:10:55,842 --> 00:10:57,843
My kids would go to school.
"What does your dad do?"

165
00:10:57,844 --> 00:11:00,512
"My dad's a policeman."
"My dad's a fireman."
"My dad's a banker."

166
00:11:00,513 --> 00:11:03,513
"And what does your dad do?"
"Oh, he's a venture capitalist."

167
00:11:04,183 --> 00:11:07,183
"Dad, what do you do actually?"
You know?

168
00:11:08,221 --> 00:11:11,221
We were just stumbling around,
trying to figure out what to do.

169
00:11:11,658 --> 00:11:14,658
But we just knew that ifwe got
involved with good people
and good markets,

170
00:11:15,328 --> 00:11:17,162
we could probably
build a company.

171
00:11:17,163 --> 00:11:18,597
Growing companies.

172
00:11:18,598 --> 00:11:21,266
Create companies.

173
00:11:21,267 --> 00:11:24,267
You're helping to create something
where nothing existed before.

174
00:11:25,571 --> 00:11:28,571
And quite a large community
gets sustenance...

175
00:11:29,175 --> 00:11:32,175
that wouldn't have existed
unless you had gotten together
with this entrepreneur...

176
00:11:33,413 --> 00:11:36,413
and his team
and helped him along the way.

177
00:11:40,620 --> 00:11:43,121
The Lunch Group had established
a good formula.

178
00:11:43,122 --> 00:11:46,122
Everyone was sharing
in the profits and success
at these fledgling companies.

179
00:11:48,695 --> 00:11:51,695
But over at Fairchild
it was a different story.

180
00:11:52,632 --> 00:11:55,632
Fairchild was an imperfect vehicle.

181
00:11:59,105 --> 00:12:02,105
I joined Fairchild
at the end of the '50s.

182
00:12:03,810 --> 00:12:06,810
I was not part of the Traitorous Eight.

183
00:12:09,415 --> 00:12:12,415
Fairchild was owned
by a corporation.

184
00:12:14,787 --> 00:12:16,421
An eastern corporation,

185
00:12:16,422 --> 00:12:19,422
and the sense of
division ofequity...

186
00:12:19,592 --> 00:12:22,592
was both unknown to them
and repugnant to them.

187
00:12:24,731 --> 00:12:27,731
All of the East Coast companies
had this hierarchy.

188
00:12:29,502 --> 00:12:32,170
And they didn't understand...

189
00:12:32,171 --> 00:12:35,171
about giving options
to all the employees...

190
00:12:36,576 --> 00:12:39,576
the way West Coast start-ups
saw fit to do.

191
00:12:41,180 --> 00:12:44,180
So none of the people
in Fairchild, including me,

192
00:12:46,452 --> 00:12:49,452
had any kind ofsignificant
ownership position.

193
00:12:52,525 --> 00:12:55,427
So, in the early '60s,

194
00:12:55,428 --> 00:12:58,428
people began leaving Fairchild
to set up start-ups...

195
00:12:59,599 --> 00:13:02,599
and to begin to participate
in what people correctly realized...

196
00:13:04,103 --> 00:13:07,103
was going to be
something special.

197
00:13:12,411 --> 00:13:15,411
Meanwhile,
back at his desk in New York-

198
00:13:15,715 --> 00:13:18,715
Well, I had wanted to do more
of these venture capital type deals,

199
00:13:20,987 --> 00:13:23,822
but the money was all in the east.

200
00:13:23,823 --> 00:13:26,823
And the scientists who had moved
from the east to the west...

201
00:13:28,127 --> 00:13:29,594
had all the ideas.

202
00:13:29,595 --> 00:13:32,595
So I saw a great opportunity
in bringing the East Coast money out...

203
00:13:34,801 --> 00:13:37,801
backing these people
on the West Coast.

204
00:13:38,037 --> 00:13:40,272
"Go West, young man."

205
00:13:40,273 --> 00:13:43,273
In 1961,
Arthur Rock raised five million dollars
from East Coast investors...

206
00:13:46,445 --> 00:13:49,445
and moved to San Francisco
to start his own
venture capital firm.

207
00:13:51,083 --> 00:13:52,684
He found a partner in Tommy Davis,

208
00:13:52,685 --> 00:13:55,685
who had been managing investments
for a California oil company.

209
00:13:58,257 --> 00:14:01,257
Davis and Rock quickly became
the biggest venture players in town,

210
00:14:02,762 --> 00:14:05,762
funding a series ofhugely
successful technology companies.

211
00:14:07,500 --> 00:14:10,500
And in the close-knit
Silicon Valley community
of the 1960s,

212
00:14:11,037 --> 00:14:13,839
it was only a matter oftime
before Arthur Rock...

213
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:16,840
would once again cross paths
with the Traitorous Eight.

214
00:14:26,152 --> 00:14:29,152
Throughout the 1960s,
Fairchild was bleeding talent.

215
00:14:30,156 --> 00:14:32,791
The lure ofstock options
and independence...

216
00:14:32,792 --> 00:14:35,393
inspired many of
the brilliant young engineers...

217
00:14:35,394 --> 00:14:38,394
to peel off
and start their own companies.

218
00:14:38,931 --> 00:14:41,931
But Gordon Moore and Bob Noyce,
its two most important founders,

219
00:14:42,602 --> 00:14:44,803
remained loyal to their company-

220
00:14:44,804 --> 00:14:47,105
until May of1968,

221
00:14:47,106 --> 00:14:50,106
when Fairchild's East Coast
management made a fatal mistake.

222
00:14:52,311 --> 00:14:55,311
Noyce was the logical internal
candidate to be the next C.E.O.

223
00:14:57,984 --> 00:15:00,984
But they decided they were gonna
look on the outside.

224
00:15:01,687 --> 00:15:04,687
That changed the whole ball game.

225
00:15:05,258 --> 00:15:08,258
Noyce said, "I'm gonna leave.
Are you interested?"

226
00:15:14,400 --> 00:15:17,400
So I said, "Okay. Let's do it."

227
00:15:20,106 --> 00:15:22,574
They needed financing,
and they called me...

228
00:15:22,575 --> 00:15:25,575
to see whether I'd be interested.

229
00:15:25,811 --> 00:15:27,812
They came to me
with no business plan,

230
00:15:27,813 --> 00:15:30,813
other than what they verbally
said they wanted to do.

231
00:15:31,951 --> 00:15:34,951
Arthur said he needed something
to talk to potential investors with.

232
00:15:35,821 --> 00:15:38,821
Just to give people something.

233
00:15:40,159 --> 00:15:42,961
We wrote a business plan,
and it was one page-

234
00:15:42,962 --> 00:15:44,896
Double-spaced,
and that was it.

235
00:15:47,500 --> 00:15:50,500
It just says we were going
to make things out ofsilicon,

236
00:15:50,836 --> 00:15:53,836
and some interesting
electronic devices.

237
00:15:54,140 --> 00:15:57,140
Oh, I said in general terms
we were going to make memories.

