00:19:05,764 --> 00:19:08,299
Shortly after Arthur Rock
went out on his own,

282
00:19:08,300 --> 00:19:10,835
Forbes profiled him
in an article that caught the eye...

283
00:19:10,836 --> 00:19:13,771
ofa young investment manager
in Boston.

284
00:19:13,772 --> 00:19:16,307
When they said,
"Well, now that you and Mr. Davis...

285
00:19:16,308 --> 00:19:18,076
are doing separate things,
what are you going to do?"

286
00:19:18,077 --> 00:19:21,012
He said, "Well, I'm gonna
find a younger partner
and do it all over again."

287
00:19:21,013 --> 00:19:24,013
And I said, "You know, gee."

288
00:19:24,617 --> 00:19:27,617
I had never even-
I mean, it was a light bulb.

289
00:19:29,788 --> 00:19:32,423
And I sat down and I wrote him
a longhand letter.

290
00:19:32,424 --> 00:19:35,424
And I never had ever done
anything like this before.

291
00:19:35,928 --> 00:19:38,663
The following Monday
I got a telephone call.

292
00:19:38,664 --> 00:19:41,299
"Mr. Rock's on the line."
I said, "Really?"

293
00:19:41,300 --> 00:19:44,300
Dick's letter was very intriguing.

294
00:19:44,737 --> 00:19:47,737
He's just generally knowledgeable
and on the same, uh, piano as I was.

295
00:19:51,076 --> 00:19:54,076
And then I found out later
that there were over a thousand
responses to the article.

296
00:19:56,549 --> 00:19:59,549
And that Arthur had
a handwriting expert
that analyzed my letter.

297
00:20:01,453 --> 00:20:03,555
Isn't that funny?

298
00:20:03,556 --> 00:20:06,556
So that's how I got
in the venture business.

299
00:20:12,631 --> 00:20:14,933
Well, you know,
there are no firm rules...

300
00:20:14,934 --> 00:20:16,968
in the venture capital business,

301
00:20:16,969 --> 00:20:19,037
except that there are no firm rules.

302
00:20:19,038 --> 00:20:22,038
Did you have any problems
in convincing your colleagues?

303
00:20:22,308 --> 00:20:25,308
Oh, yeah, they thought I was
out ofmy mind on this one.

304
00:20:26,278 --> 00:20:29,278
By the early '70s, inspired
by the success ofArthur Rock,

305
00:20:30,282 --> 00:20:33,251
more members of the Lunch Group
began to quit their day jobs...

306
00:20:33,252 --> 00:20:35,753
and setup
their own venture funds.

307
00:20:35,754 --> 00:20:38,754
Reid Dennis gave notice
to his boss at American Express.

308
00:20:39,658 --> 00:20:42,658
He said, "Reid, are you sure
this is what you want to do?"

309
00:20:42,728 --> 00:20:45,728
I said, "Bill, I've never been
so sure ofanything in all my life."

310
00:20:46,365 --> 00:20:48,866
He said, "Well, wereally
don't want you to go,

311
00:20:48,867 --> 00:20:51,867
but ifyou're determined to go'
you ought to take
some ofour money with you."

312
00:20:54,373 --> 00:20:56,474
And that's what gave
us the impetus...

313
00:20:56,475 --> 00:20:59,475
to start Institutional
Venture Associates.

314
00:21:00,913 --> 00:21:03,913
A career
in venture capital now
seemed so alluring,

315
00:21:04,049 --> 00:21:06,050
and potentially so profitable,

316
00:21:06,051 --> 00:21:09,051
it was attracting people
outside offinance.

317
00:21:09,722 --> 00:21:11,322
Two Silicon Valley engineers,

318
00:21:11,323 --> 00:21:14,323
Eugene Kleiner and Tom Perkins,

319
00:21:14,560 --> 00:21:16,828
formed what would become
one of the most successful...

320
00:21:16,829 --> 00:21:19,829
venture firms ofall time.

321
00:21:21,467 --> 00:21:24,467
Well, I sort ofgot into venture
capital by the back door.

322
00:21:26,071 --> 00:21:29,071
I was working for the
Hewlett-Packard company...

323
00:21:29,775 --> 00:21:32,775
when I had an idea
for a radically improved
kind oflaser.

324
00:21:34,580 --> 00:21:37,048
And then I started a company...

325
00:21:37,049 --> 00:21:39,217
to manufacture the lasers.

326
00:21:39,218 --> 00:21:40,852
When it was all over I realized,

327
00:21:40,853 --> 00:21:43,288
gee, I had been
a venture capitalist.

328
00:21:43,289 --> 00:21:46,289
I put up the money.
I put up the management.

329
00:21:47,660 --> 00:21:50,660
So then when I met Gene Kleiner,
who had left Fairchild,

330
00:21:52,097 --> 00:21:55,097
we were both planning
to go into the venture
capital business.

331
00:21:56,869 --> 00:21:59,869
And werealized
we complemented each other.

332
00:22:01,307 --> 00:22:03,541
I mean I'm pretty intense
and high-strung'

333
00:22:03,542 --> 00:22:06,044
and Gene was
sort ofcalm and portly...

334
00:22:06,045 --> 00:22:09,045
and had a soothing
Viennese accent.

335
00:22:10,115 --> 00:22:13,115
Eugene was just brilliant.
He was fun to be with.

336
00:22:14,820 --> 00:22:17,820
I remember once we met
an entrepreneur,

337
00:22:17,823 --> 00:22:20,758
and after he left I said, "Gene,

338
00:22:20,759 --> 00:22:23,759
you know, do you trust him?"

339
00:22:24,163 --> 00:22:27,163
And Gene said,
"I would trust him with my life,
but not my money."

340
00:22:32,838 --> 00:22:35,740
And that's how it started.

341
00:22:35,741 --> 00:22:38,276
We hung out our shingle'

342
00:22:38,277 --> 00:22:40,311
and nothing happened.

343
00:22:40,312 --> 00:22:43,312
The phone didn't ring.
We had a part-time secretary-

344
00:22:44,016 --> 00:22:46,284
We called out,
nobody called in.

345
00:22:46,285 --> 00:22:49,285
We saw some deals,
and we did some deals.

346
00:22:51,256 --> 00:22:54,256
We lost money
in our original deals.

347
00:22:55,194 --> 00:22:57,962
And I'll mention them,
even though they were
very embarrassing.

348
00:22:57,963 --> 00:23:00,963
The most notorious,
and maybe the funniest'

349
00:23:01,266 --> 00:23:02,867
was a company called Snow Job-

350
00:23:04,203 --> 00:23:07,203
Which was a scheme to convert
motorcycles into snowmobiles...

351
00:23:08,474 --> 00:23:10,108
and back and forth.

352
00:23:10,109 --> 00:23:12,877
Which actually worked,
and it was a lot offun,

353
00:23:12,878 --> 00:23:15,878
But one of the fuel crises
landed at about the time we were
ready to go into production,

354
00:23:18,484 --> 00:23:21,484
and we couldn't get distributors,
and, uh, so it failed.

355
00:23:26,825 --> 00:23:29,825
So Eugene and I thought'
you know, "This is not working.

356
00:23:30,129 --> 00:23:33,129
We've got to do
something differently."

357
00:23:39,004 --> 00:23:42,004
Tandem was a huge risk
for Kleiner Perkins.

358
00:23:42,007 --> 00:23:45,007
IfTandem had failed,
there would have never been
a second Kleiner Perkins fund.

359
00:23:51,016 --> 00:23:53,418
I think I was 33.

360
00:23:53,419 --> 00:23:56,419
I was young, in terms ofpeople
starting companies,

361
00:23:57,556 --> 00:23:59,791
but there weren't a lot
ofpeople starting companies, so-

362
00:24:01,226 --> 00:24:04,226
Well, Jimmy Treybig-
very smart guy.
Very impressive.

363
00:24:06,632 --> 00:24:09,632
He had this idea,
which he'd carried-

364
00:24:09,902 --> 00:24:12,902
not the technical part ofit,
but the need...

365
00:24:13,739 --> 00:24:15,973
for a truly fault-tolerant
computer.

366
00:24:15,974 --> 00:24:18,974
A computer
that would never fail.

367
00:24:20,512 --> 00:24:23,512
At that time, for instance,
the New York Stock Exchange...

368
00:24:23,749 --> 00:24:26,749
would fail about every day,
or every other day.

369
00:24:27,986 --> 00:24:30,986
And something
would go wrong in it,
and it would destroy data.

370
00:24:37,162 --> 00:24:39,897
People knew the problem,
but they didn't have a solution.

371
00:24:39,898 --> 00:24:42,898
So just think ofit.
I mean, credit checking,
airline reservations, banking.

372
00:24:43,535 --> 00:24:45,136
All financial things.

373
00:24:45,137 --> 00:24:47,605
- Hospitals.
- All communications.

374
00:24:47,606 --> 00:24:49,507
Just all kinds ofthings...

375
00:24:49,508 --> 00:24:52,508
where it's just not acceptable
to have the computer go down.

376
00:24:55,814 --> 00:24:58,015
We knew-Tom and I knew-

377
00:24:58,016 --> 00:25:01,016
that ifwe could figure out
a different kind
ofcomputer architecture...

378
00:25:01,687 --> 00:25:04,687
to solve this problem,
that we could create a big company.

379
00:25:09,228 --> 00:25:12,228
The problem was IBM had won
the mainframe battle in '74.

380
00:25:13,465 --> 00:25:16,465
And there was an article
that said there would never
be a new computer company.

381
00:25:18,570 --> 00:25:20,605
Never. That was '74.

382
00:25:20,606 --> 00:25:23,606
And the cover was a picture
ofa shark,

383
00:25:24,943 --> 00:25:27,943
and IBM was eating up
every company.

384
00:25:29,882 --> 00:25:32,882
When you think about
what decisions are being made,

385
00:25:33,485 --> 00:25:36,485
you got IBM wiping out GE,
Siemens.

386
00:25:38,824 --> 00:25:41,824
So it would be easy not to
want to go after that, right?

387
00:25:43,195 --> 00:25:46,195
So you have to be brave.
I mean, you have to see it,
and you have to be brave.

388
00:25:47,466 --> 00:25:50,466
And being brave is one thing
you got to say about Tom.

389
00:25:54,506 --> 00:25:57,506
You gotta look to get money
from strong people.

390
00:25:58,110 --> 00:26:01,110
Because weak people
don't invest in tough times.

391
00:26:02,915 --> 00:26:05,915
But that's when most of
the big winners are created.

392
00:26:12,758 --> 00:26:15,758
Well, first ofall, we didn't want
to be the only backers ofTandem.

393
00:26:17,129 --> 00:26:20,129
We tried to raise venture capital.
I made a trip back east.

394
00:26:20,899 --> 00:26:23,899
I remember the first time
we gave the pitch.

395
00:26:23,936 --> 00:26:26,936
Jimmy was straight out ofTexas,
a real character,

396
00:26:29,408 --> 00:26:31,842
and I didn't think he'd go over
very well on Wall Street.

397
00:26:31,843 --> 00:26:34,843
He had to take me to buy a suit.
He probably shared that.

398
00:26:36,281 --> 00:26:39,281
I literally took him to Brooks Brothers.
And shoes, socks, the works.

399
00:26:40,719 --> 00:26:43,154
He always said, uh-
I forget what he said,

400
00:26:43,155 --> 00:26:46,155
but, "He could buy the suit,
and that still didn't help."

401
00:26:46,625 --> 00:26:49,625
And took him back to Wall Street,
and ofcourse the first thing he said is,

402
00:26:50,162 --> 00:26:52,830
"Well, how do I look?
Tom dressed me!"

403
00:26:52,831 --> 00:26:54,365
You know-

404
00:26:54,366 --> 00:26:57,366
Tom was, uh, a little more
sophisticated than me.

405
00:26:58,203 --> 00:27:01,203
But we didn't get the money.

406
00:27:03,175 --> 00:27:06,175
Untried management.
An unlikely idea.

407
00:27:08,146 --> 00:27:11,146
Most people
would not have thought this
was gonna be a big winner.

408
00:27:13,485 --> 00:27:16,485
But I felt strongly enough
about Tandem that, uh,

409
00:27:16,955 --> 00:27:19,955
even ifwe had to put up
all the money, we would do it.

410
00:27:20,993 --> 00:27:23,993
And then finally, at the last minute,
Pitch Johnson put in
a small investment.

411
00:27:26,131 --> 00:27:28,599
I like to think that
Tom felt my presence...

412
00:27:28,600 --> 00:27:30,735
would be helpful
in raising money elsewhere.

413
00:27:30,736 --> 00:27:32,703
It ratified our concept.

414
00:27:32,704 --> 00:27:34,872
I was credible in those days.

415
00:27:34,873 --> 00:27:37,873
Hi. I'm standing here next to
a beautiful Tandem computer.

416
00:27:37,876 --> 00:27:40,876
I think everyone recognizes
this fine computer.

417
00:27:41,146 --> 00:27:44,146
It took us a long time
to get that first order.

418
00:27:44,182 --> 00:27:47,182
The very first customer
was Citibank.

419
00:27:48,720 --> 00:27:50,388
But when we got the first order,

420
00:27:50,389 --> 00:27:53,389
and the computers performed
as expected, even better,

421
00:27:54,493 --> 00:27:57,328
the growth took off
and became explosive.

422
00:27:57,329 --> 00:27:58,696
We went seven,

423
00:27:58,697 --> 00:28:00,831
25, 50, 100 million,

424
00:28:00,832 --> 00:28:03,000
200 million, on up to a billion,

425
00:28:03,001 --> 00:28:06,001
and we were a Fortune 500
company in '82.

426
00:28:13,912 --> 00:28:16,912
You use a Tandem computer today...

427
00:28:17,449 --> 00:28:20,449
pretty much any time you use
your credit card for anything.

428
00:28:36,301 --> 00:28:38,736
When I started
in the venture business,

429
00:28:38,737 --> 00:28:41,737
it never occurred to me
that we would have multiple funds...

430
00:28:44,176 --> 00:28:47,176
that would easily exceed
a billion dollars.

431
00:28:49,114 --> 00:28:52,114
I got into the business
somewhat fortuitously.

432
00:28:53,885 --> 00:28:56,885
When I made the decision,

433
00:28:56,888 --> 00:28:59,888
I had already put in 13 years
working in real companies.

434
00:29:02,561 --> 00:29:05,196
In 1972, Don Valentine decided...

435
00:29:05,197 --> 00:29:08,197
to trade on his connections
in the semiconductor industry...

436
00:29:08,433 --> 00:29:11,433
and went in search of capital
to start a venture fund.

437
00:29:13,605 --> 00:29:16,605
We went to see a guy
at Salomon Brothers,

438
00:29:17,275 --> 00:29:19,977
and he said "You know'
I've listened to the pitch,

439
00:29:19,978 --> 00:29:22,978
but, you know, you didn't go
to Harvard Business School."

440
00:29:24,983 --> 00:29:27,983
I said, "Great observation.
True. Guilty as charged."

441
00:29:29,788 --> 00:29:31,822
He says, "Why didn't you
go to business school?"

442
00:29:31,823 --> 00:29:34,823
I said, "I went to Fairchild
Semiconductor Business School.
Great business school.

443
00:29:36,495 --> 00:29:39,495
Start-up company.
Pioneer in a technology.

444
00:29:40,098 --> 00:29:43,098
Phenomenal leadership
and recognition."

445
00:29:44,569 --> 00:29:47,569
I said, "I don't need
to go to a business school
for what I'm gonna do."

446
00:29:51,543 --> 00:29:53,310
Rebuffed by Wall Street,

447
00:29:53,311 --> 00:29:55,279
Don Valentine found a mentor...

448
00:29:55,280 --> 00:29:57,782
in a Southern California
mutual fund manager...

449
00:29:57,783 --> 00:30:00,783
who staked th emoney for Don's
first venturefund.

450
00:30:01,720 --> 00:30:04,720
I'm not interested in entrepreneurs
who will do it our way.

451
00:30:07,125 --> 00:30:10,125
I'm not interested
in entrepreneurs
who think there's a dress code.

452
00:30:11,930 --> 00:30:14,930
I'm interested in entrepreneurs
who have a vision...

453
00:30:15,734 --> 00:30:18,734
