preferably that becomes big.

454
00:30:26,344 --> 00:30:28,679
For most people,
there's something intimidating...

455
00:30:28,680 --> 00:30:31,649
about the idea of interacting
with a computer,

456
00:30:31,650 --> 00:30:34,318
but that is
what's happening here.

457
00:30:34,319 --> 00:30:37,288
Atari had one of Silicon Valley's...

458
00:30:37,289 --> 00:30:40,257
absolutely larger-than-life
personalities leading it,

459
00:30:40,258 --> 00:30:43,258
Nolan K. Bushnell.

460
00:30:44,196 --> 00:30:46,197
Bushnell was a young engineer...

461
00:30:46,198 --> 00:30:48,966
working for game manufacturer
Nutting Associates...

462
00:30:48,967 --> 00:30:51,967
when he decided to strike out
on his own in 1972.

463
00:30:53,638 --> 00:30:56,638
The real thing that
allowed me to start Atari...

464
00:30:56,875 --> 00:30:58,976
was I worked for Nutting,

465
00:30:58,977 --> 00:31:01,977
and these guys couldn't find
their butts with both hands.

466
00:31:02,247 --> 00:31:04,815
I said, "You know,
I can run a company,

467
00:31:04,816 --> 00:31:07,816
and I won't make any of these same
mistakes these idiots are doing."

468
00:31:10,755 --> 00:31:13,657
The first game
Atari designed was Pong.

469
00:31:15,527 --> 00:31:18,527
Nolan took a prototype of the game,
strapped it to his back...

470
00:31:18,563 --> 00:31:21,563
and placed it in a bar
in Sunnyvale, California.

471
00:31:22,334 --> 00:31:25,334
By the next morning,
customers were lined up outside...

472
00:31:25,337 --> 00:31:28,337
clamoring for a chance to play.

473
00:31:28,506 --> 00:31:30,908
We put it on location.
It earned a lot ofmoney.

474
00:31:30,909 --> 00:31:33,909
Production soared, and there seemed
to be an insatiable appetite...

475
00:31:35,714 --> 00:31:37,681
for the coin-operated game.

476
00:31:39,985 --> 00:31:42,985
From the outside, Atari looked
like a wildly successful company,

477
00:31:44,089 --> 00:31:47,089
producing an endless stream
of popular games.

478
00:31:47,359 --> 00:31:50,160
But there was one key problem.

479
00:31:52,097 --> 00:31:55,097
The company was started
with 250 dollars.

480
00:31:55,333 --> 00:31:58,333
And so we never had any money.

481
00:32:00,205 --> 00:32:03,205
If you're
a hardware company, you need
a lot of capital for inventories.

482
00:32:05,377 --> 00:32:08,112
The more successful,
the moreyou have to raise.

483
00:32:08,113 --> 00:32:10,214
Because the more inventory
you have,

484
00:32:10,215 --> 00:32:13,215
the more customers
you're waiting to pay you.

485
00:32:13,485 --> 00:32:16,485
It takes a lot of capital
for a hardware start-up.

486
00:32:17,022 --> 00:32:20,022
In 1974 Atari was
flirting with bankruptcy...

487
00:32:21,026 --> 00:32:24,026
and desperately needed
financial help.

488
00:32:24,062 --> 00:32:27,062
But Nolan found
the traditional channels off-limits.

489
00:32:28,700 --> 00:32:31,700
Banks-
in the traditional sense of banks-
lend on assets.

490
00:32:33,772 --> 00:32:36,173
So, "Do you have a house?
I'll give you a mortgage.

491
00:32:36,174 --> 00:32:39,174
Doyou have a car?
I'll giveyou a loan on your car."

492
00:32:41,046 --> 00:32:44,046
Nolan had no basis
for a bank to be comfortable.

493
00:32:47,886 --> 00:32:50,886
I went through the factory,

494
00:32:51,656 --> 00:32:54,656
and the smell of marijuana
nearly knocked me to my knees.

495
00:32:57,329 --> 00:32:59,997
And I was gasping and coughing.

496
00:32:59,998 --> 00:33:02,066
Nolan says, "What's the matter?"

497
00:33:02,067 --> 00:33:05,067
And I said, "I don't know
what those people are smoking,
but it's not my brand."

498
00:33:07,539 --> 00:33:09,373
Don might have passed on Atari...

499
00:33:09,374 --> 00:33:12,374
had Nolan not shown him
a surprising new product
in development-

500
00:33:15,447 --> 00:33:17,881
Home Pong

501
00:33:17,882 --> 00:33:20,882
Atari's engineers
had discovered they could
get the entire Pong game...

502
00:33:21,753 --> 00:33:24,753
down to the size of a shoe box.

503
00:33:25,256 --> 00:33:28,256
At the time, playing
video games at home
was a revolutionary concept.

504
00:33:31,496 --> 00:33:34,496
We showed Don our plans
for the home games.

505
00:33:36,401 --> 00:33:39,036
He finally decided
there was a business there.

506
00:33:39,037 --> 00:33:42,037
Fabulous product.
Giant market.

507
00:33:43,241 --> 00:33:46,176
He used to say, you know,
"The coin-op business-
you think it's big?"

508
00:33:46,177 --> 00:33:48,245
He says, "You ain't seen nothin'."

509
00:33:48,246 --> 00:33:49,847
Huge.

510
00:33:51,850 --> 00:33:54,084
Once we decided
to finance Atari,

511
00:33:54,085 --> 00:33:57,085
it was a matter of trying
to figure out who else
would invest in it.

512
00:34:00,458 --> 00:34:03,458
Funds in those days were tiny,

513
00:34:03,561 --> 00:34:06,561
and in order for us
to start a company,

514
00:34:06,865 --> 00:34:09,865
we had to very collegially
work together.

515
00:34:13,638 --> 00:34:16,638
I brought him other investors.

516
00:34:17,342 --> 00:34:20,342
However, it takes a while
to get used to Nolan.

517
00:34:23,481 --> 00:34:26,083
And there's a story there
about one of our meetings,

518
00:34:26,084 --> 00:34:29,084
where the man from Fidelity
was sitting in a chair
with his blue suit on,

519
00:34:30,055 --> 00:34:32,656
and the rest of us
were in the hot tub.

520
00:34:32,657 --> 00:34:35,657
Nolan was unrelentingly
picking on him...

521
00:34:35,827 --> 00:34:38,827
about his prudish behavior
and why he wouldn't get
in the hot tub.

522
00:34:41,633 --> 00:34:43,767
With a controversial
entrepreneur...

523
00:34:43,768 --> 00:34:46,336
and no existing market
for home video games,

524
00:34:46,337 --> 00:34:49,337
months went by
while the other investors remained
on the fence about Atari.

525
00:34:51,743 --> 00:34:54,743
So Nolan himself
took his Home Pong prototype
on the road in search of customers.

526
00:34:57,415 --> 00:34:59,817
Of course, we were young
and felt we could solve...

527
00:34:59,818 --> 00:35:02,818
any problems that came along,
and, you know,

528
00:35:02,854 --> 00:35:05,854
selling them to Toys R Us,
that can't be that hard.

529
00:35:07,392 --> 00:35:09,226
It was, actually.

530
00:35:09,227 --> 00:35:11,028
I like to tell the story about...

531
00:35:11,029 --> 00:35:14,029
taking the Pong game
to the toy fair in New York
and selling none.

532
00:35:17,435 --> 00:35:20,435
So we thought,
"Let's try the television shops."

533
00:35:20,939 --> 00:35:23,939
And they didn't want it.

534
00:35:26,144 --> 00:35:29,144
These are very fragile companies
with a lot of things missing.

535
00:35:30,815 --> 00:35:33,584
And the approach
we've always taken is,

536
00:35:33,585 --> 00:35:36,585
if we make this investment,
is our Rolodex...

537
00:35:36,688 --> 00:35:39,688
strong enough
to help these people?

538
00:35:43,361 --> 00:35:46,361
So much luck
goes into these things...

539
00:35:47,565 --> 00:35:50,565
that without it, I think
very few of us would have
very many successes.

540
00:35:55,073 --> 00:35:58,073
One of our investors was
a very big shareholder of Sears.

541
00:36:00,778 --> 00:36:03,347
And they facilitated
the introduction...

542
00:36:03,348 --> 00:36:06,348
to the buyer at Sears
who would buy a product like this.

543
00:36:08,019 --> 00:36:11,019
I think he was charmed by Nolan...

544
00:36:11,256 --> 00:36:14,256
and found this experiment
might be fun.

545
00:36:14,792 --> 00:36:17,792
♪ Everybody's talkin' 'bout
a new way of shopping ♪

546
00:36:17,996 --> 00:36:20,430
♪ Doyou wanna lose your mind? ♪♪

547
00:36:20,431 --> 00:36:22,199
Home Pong hit the shelves...

548
00:36:22,200 --> 00:36:25,200
just in time
for the 1975 Christmas season.

549
00:36:25,904 --> 00:36:27,237
♪♪

550
00:36:27,238 --> 00:36:30,238
And of course, the rest is history.

