00:37:02,340 --> 00:37:05,340
My father was the sole proprietor
of this little candy store.

555
00:37:06,844 --> 00:37:09,844
My father was a very petty
union member.

556
00:37:10,782 --> 00:37:13,483
My dad was a wonderful guy,

557
00:37:13,484 --> 00:37:16,484
and, um, he really encouraged
self-reliance.

558
00:37:18,156 --> 00:37:21,156
Well, we sold a little groceries,
a little magazines,

559
00:37:21,259 --> 00:37:24,259
a little candy,
a little ice cream, cigarettes.

560
00:37:25,997 --> 00:37:28,997
At a very early age,
I worked there.

561
00:37:30,134 --> 00:37:32,402
I clerked.

562
00:37:32,403 --> 00:37:35,403
I was six years-
seven years old.

563
00:37:36,975 --> 00:37:39,975
It's easier to explain
he drove a truck...

564
00:37:40,144 --> 00:37:42,212
than it is to explain
what he did in the union,

565
00:37:42,213 --> 00:37:44,248
'cause I didn't understand
what he did in the union...

566
00:37:44,249 --> 00:37:47,249
other than fight
with the head of the union.

567
00:37:49,487 --> 00:37:52,487
And we used to have
a lot of, uh, arguments...

568
00:37:53,925 --> 00:37:55,692
once I understood
what a union was,

569
00:37:55,693 --> 00:37:58,693
and he couldn't understand
why I was so adamantly
opposed to the unions.

570
00:38:03,368 --> 00:38:06,368
It probably has to do with my...

571
00:38:07,572 --> 00:38:10,572
deep-seated
sense of disobedience.

572
00:38:11,142 --> 00:38:13,210
When I was 12 or 13,

573
00:38:13,211 --> 00:38:16,211
I was trying to figure out
how to earn some money
in the summertime.

574
00:38:16,714 --> 00:38:19,714
So I said, "You know, Dad,
maybe I could sell light bulbs."

575
00:38:23,988 --> 00:38:26,490
So I went down
to the local general manager...

576
00:38:26,491 --> 00:38:29,393
of the Sylvania operation.

577
00:38:29,394 --> 00:38:31,728
He said the smallest amount
that he could sell me...

578
00:38:31,729 --> 00:38:34,729
would be a half a freight car
full of light bulbs.

579
00:38:35,933 --> 00:38:38,933
And so I asked my mother
if I could populate our basement
with all these light bulbs.

580
00:38:40,938 --> 00:38:43,573
And so I got this wagon-
this big wagon-

581
00:38:43,574 --> 00:38:46,574
and I went around
and I sold light bulbs
for a whole summertime.

582
00:38:46,778 --> 00:38:49,246
I called it the Bright Boy
Light Bulb Company.

583
00:38:49,247 --> 00:38:52,247
It's a little bit over the top,
but that's what it was.

584
00:38:52,984 --> 00:38:55,152
I was a nerd.

585
00:38:55,153 --> 00:38:56,987
A highly motivated, impatient,

586
00:38:56,988 --> 00:38:59,988
driven
workaholic nerd.

587
00:38:59,991 --> 00:39:02,991
Um-
Who accidentally
became an athlete,

588
00:39:04,996 --> 00:39:07,996
and got some sort
of social polish...

589
00:39:09,400 --> 00:39:12,400
at a school for nerds- MIT.

590
00:39:14,305 --> 00:39:17,305
I scrambled to get into
a degree where I thought
I could earn a living,

591
00:39:18,676 --> 00:39:21,011
which was electronic engineering.

592
00:39:21,012 --> 00:39:24,012
I did that for a while, and I thought,
"God, this is pretty boring."

593
00:39:24,949 --> 00:39:27,949
And I thought, "Well, you know,
I've heard about business school.

594
00:39:29,921 --> 00:39:32,921
Maybe I should
take a crack at that."

595
00:39:34,125 --> 00:39:37,125
And this is where I got inspired
by Georges Doriot.

596
00:39:41,966 --> 00:39:43,667
Professor Georges Doriot...

597
00:39:43,668 --> 00:39:46,269
was a father figgure
to a generation of young men...

598
00:39:46,270 --> 00:39:48,305
at Harvard Business School.

599
00:39:48,306 --> 00:39:51,306
This French expatriate
had the distinction of starting..

600
00:39:51,309 --> 00:39:54,309
the first corporation dedicated
exclusively to venture investing,

601
00:39:55,613 --> 00:39:58,613
American Research
and Development,
founded in 1946.

602
00:40:01,018 --> 00:40:03,387
Ironically, Doriot's lasting impact...

603
00:40:03,388 --> 00:40:05,255
would not be through A.R.D.,

604
00:40:05,256 --> 00:40:08,256
which in its entire 25-year history
made only one notable investment.

605
00:40:11,062 --> 00:40:13,330
Instead, Doriot's
most important influence...

606
00:40:13,331 --> 00:40:16,331
came through the spell he cast
over his Harvard classroom.

607
00:40:18,169 --> 00:40:20,470
Doriot
was very controversial...

608
00:40:20,471 --> 00:40:23,306
even at the time at Harvard.

609
00:40:23,307 --> 00:40:26,276
He taught a course
called Manufacturing,

610
00:40:26,277 --> 00:40:28,912
which really had nothing to do
with manufacturing.

611
00:40:28,913 --> 00:40:31,348
And it was an extremely
popular course,

612
00:40:31,349 --> 00:40:34,349
and it was
all about starting companies,
and technology.

613
00:40:36,354 --> 00:40:39,289
He talked about entrepreneurs.
He had some of them as guests-

614
00:40:39,290 --> 00:40:40,857
what it was like
to start a company.

615
00:40:40,858 --> 00:40:43,858
His lectures were how to dress,

616
00:40:44,529 --> 00:40:47,197
how many drinks you should have
at a cocktail party.

617
00:40:47,198 --> 00:40:50,198
It was sort of a Georges Doriot
philosophy of life.

618
00:40:50,601 --> 00:40:53,601
Every year, he'd take
one whole session...

619
00:40:54,639 --> 00:40:56,540
on how to read
the New York Times.

620
00:40:56,541 --> 00:40:59,541
He'd hold up the paper and say-

621
00:40:59,710 --> 00:41:02,710
"You should be able to read
this paper in four minutes.

622
00:41:03,748 --> 00:41:06,116
What is the first section I read?"

623
00:41:06,117 --> 00:41:09,117
He said, "Now the first thing
you want to do is go
to the obituary page.

624
00:41:10,054 --> 00:41:13,054
There you will learn
the lives that are important,

625
00:41:13,825 --> 00:41:16,825
and the kind of life
that you can build for yourself."

626
00:41:18,029 --> 00:41:21,029
He would talk about working
with entrepreneurs.

627
00:41:21,332 --> 00:41:24,332
And when times got tough,
as they always will-

628
00:41:24,802 --> 00:41:26,837
and he made that point-

629
00:41:26,838 --> 00:41:29,838
that he would invite
the entrepreneur over to his home.

630
00:41:30,741 --> 00:41:33,510
They'd have dinner, and then he'd
just sit him down in his library...

631
00:41:33,511 --> 00:41:36,511
and play phonograph records
of French marching music.

632
00:41:38,850 --> 00:41:41,850
You know, just to deal with
the psychological wounds, you know.

633
00:41:44,155 --> 00:41:46,356
When he was talking about
venture capital, starting companies,

634
00:41:46,357 --> 00:41:49,025
he was as good as there was,
because he was the only guy
who understood it.

635
00:41:49,026 --> 00:41:52,026
I bought it all-
hook, line, sinker.

636
