643
00:42:34,338 --> 00:42:36,039
At the time we started Genentech,

644
00:42:36,040 --> 00:42:39,040
there was no such thing
as genetic engineering.

645
00:42:39,410 --> 00:42:42,410
And to take the idea
of commercializing gene splicing,

646
00:42:44,215 --> 00:42:46,816
the risks were just enormous.

647
00:42:50,254 --> 00:42:52,289
And I said, "Well, you know,

648
00:42:52,290 --> 00:42:55,290
what if God or Darwin
won't let us
make a new life form?"

649
00:43:05,570 --> 00:43:08,471
It was a bet on technology,

650
00:43:08,472 --> 00:43:11,472
and you looked
at the value of the
pharmaceutical industry,

651
00:43:11,576 --> 00:43:14,576
and if you had a better
way to develop drugs,

652
00:43:15,246 --> 00:43:18,246
the power was enormous.

653
00:43:18,416 --> 00:43:21,416
Nobody had a clue
whether they could pull that off,

654
00:43:21,786 --> 00:43:24,786
but you did know...
that if they could, it was big.

655
00:43:34,231 --> 00:43:37,231
It came out of the blue for me.

656
00:43:38,202 --> 00:43:41,202
I had not been thinking
about starting a company.

657
00:43:43,541 --> 00:43:46,541
I thought I was going to,
uh, die at the lab bench
with a pipette in my mouth.

658
00:43:48,412 --> 00:43:51,412
But, uh, Bob called,

659
00:43:51,949 --> 00:43:54,949
and he wanted to know
if the technology was
ready to be commercialized.

660
00:43:58,556 --> 00:44:01,556
Bob Swanson,
I think, was the most prescient
individual I've ever met.

661
00:44:04,328 --> 00:44:05,895
Once he understood...

662
00:44:05,896 --> 00:44:08,896
what the potential technology was
in genetic engineering,

663
00:44:09,900 --> 00:44:12,900
he got the whole picture,
way ahead ofanybody else.

664
00:44:16,907 --> 00:44:19,907
Eugene and I were looking around
for someone to add to the partnership,

665
00:44:21,178 --> 00:44:23,346
and Bobjoined us.

666
00:44:23,347 --> 00:44:26,347
But there just wasn't enough
going on in those days, amazingly,

667
00:44:27,418 --> 00:44:30,418
to really have him
full-time working on our ventures.

668
00:44:31,155 --> 00:44:33,390
We didn't have that many.

669
00:44:33,391 --> 00:44:36,391
But we were interested
in doing something
in genetic engineering.

670
00:44:37,628 --> 00:44:40,628
We sort of said,
"Go there, find something.

671
00:44:40,765 --> 00:44:43,299
And if you can, we'll finance it.

672
00:44:43,300 --> 00:44:46,300
If you can't, well-"
You know.

673
00:44:46,337 --> 00:44:49,337
So he was motivated
to find something.

674
00:44:50,574 --> 00:44:53,574
And he calls Professor Boyer
at the University of California.

675
00:44:55,112 --> 00:44:57,180
Boyer said,
"I'll give you five minutes."

676
00:44:57,181 --> 00:45:00,181
It turned into,
you know, many hours.

677
00:45:01,085 --> 00:45:04,085
In those days, funding
for research was, uh, difficult.

678
00:45:06,157 --> 00:45:09,157
And so, you know,
I had some, you know,
ulterior reasons...

679
00:45:12,029 --> 00:45:15,029
for paying attention
when he said he had money.

680
00:45:16,367 --> 00:45:19,367
Over the next couple of weeks,
Swanson persuaded Boyer...

681
00:45:20,337 --> 00:45:23,337
to take the idea of gene splicing
into some sort
of a commercial operation.

682
00:45:26,377 --> 00:45:29,377
And Bob brought Boyer to me.

683
00:45:34,552 --> 00:45:37,552
So we go into one of
the, uh, Embarcadero Towers,

684
00:45:39,790 --> 00:45:42,790
and we go up to the top floor.

685
00:45:43,327 --> 00:45:46,327
And you can
look out over the world.

686
00:45:49,633 --> 00:45:52,633
It was something like
out of a movie,
and holy smoke.

687
00:45:55,439 --> 00:45:58,439
So we go in, and these
stern-looking guys are sitting
there in a suit, you know.

688
00:46:02,346 --> 00:46:04,414
Perkins says,
"Okay, Well, what are you going to do?"

689
00:46:04,415 --> 00:46:07,283
What do you do?
What equipment do you need?

690
00:46:07,284 --> 00:46:09,719
How do you know
that you've done it?
How do you test?

691
00:46:09,720 --> 00:46:11,421
It's scary.

692
00:46:11,422 --> 00:46:14,422
What are the risks? Contamination?
Everything I could think-

693
00:46:14,759 --> 00:46:17,759
Here was this rich guy, you know,
talking to us about science,
and funding science.

694
00:46:19,330 --> 00:46:21,264
I paid attention, you know.

695
00:46:21,265 --> 00:46:24,100
And I didn't know anything
about raising money.

696
00:46:24,101 --> 00:46:27,101
Of course, I knew nothing
whatsoever about the technology.
I mean, nobody did.

697
00:46:28,139 --> 00:46:29,506
I had to rely on him.

698
00:46:29,507 --> 00:46:31,141
Because there was so much
to be done.

699
00:46:31,142 --> 00:46:32,909
He was a very hands-on guy.

700
00:46:32,910 --> 00:46:35,910
They wanted to raise, um'
about three million dollars
to build the factory,

701
00:46:38,249 --> 00:46:41,249
hire the people,
and then see if it would work.

702
00:46:42,620 --> 00:46:44,287
But underlying it all...

