981
01:06:19,462 --> 01:06:22,462
In 1984 Cisco Systems
was a two-person company-

982
01:06:23,866 --> 01:06:26,866
The husband-and-wife team
of Len Bosack and Sandy Lerner.

983
01:06:27,971 --> 01:06:29,938
Cisco was a typical start-up.

984
01:06:29,939 --> 01:06:31,907
It was certainly
run out of our house.

985
01:06:31,908 --> 01:06:34,908
A number of very
illustrious companies
I think have that distinction.

986
01:06:37,547 --> 01:06:40,547
through Cisco, Sandy and Len
were early evangelists...

987
01:06:40,583 --> 01:06:43,185
for what would one day
be called the Internet,

988
01:06:43,186 --> 01:06:46,186
but which, in 1984,
was really just a jury-rigged
network of computers,

989
01:06:47,724 --> 01:06:50,724
used at universities
and in the military.

990
01:06:51,294 --> 01:06:53,528
Cisco's product
was called a router.

991
01:06:53,529 --> 01:06:56,164
And it solved a very big problem.

992
01:06:56,165 --> 01:06:59,165
It allowed all kinds of computer
systems to talk to each other easily
for the very first time.

993
01:07:03,706 --> 01:07:06,706
This opened the door
to the development
of an online world.

994
01:07:08,978 --> 01:07:11,978
It was a desperately-needed
product.

995
01:07:12,482 --> 01:07:15,482
But... no one would finance Cisco.

996
01:07:20,923 --> 01:07:23,923
We tried from the very beginning
to-to get funding.

997
01:07:24,560 --> 01:07:26,862
Uh, we just
weren't successful.

998
01:07:26,863 --> 01:07:29,331
We were not the first people
to see it,

999
01:07:29,332 --> 01:07:32,134
as armies of people
have told me-

1000
01:07:32,135 --> 01:07:34,903
That they saw it before we did,
and they turned it down.

1001
01:07:34,904 --> 01:07:37,904
They took the position
that this wasn't
a tenable business model.

1002
01:07:38,241 --> 01:07:41,241
I-I don't think, in their position,
I would have disagreed
with that.

1003
01:07:43,079 --> 01:07:46,079
But I wasn't in their position,
and I did disagree with it.

1004
01:07:46,349 --> 01:07:49,349
These things are not so clear.

1005
01:07:49,452 --> 01:07:52,452
Different people
see them differently.

1006
01:07:52,588 --> 01:07:55,588
The person who got us involved
with Cisco said,

1007
01:07:56,292 --> 01:07:59,292
"You are probably the only person
in North America...

1008
01:07:59,562 --> 01:08:02,562
who would be willing to deal
with these people."

1009
01:08:02,899 --> 01:08:05,467
The people at Cisco-

1010
01:08:05,468 --> 01:08:08,468
If you were designing
hard-to-get-along-with
people,

1011
01:08:09,372 --> 01:08:11,740
they got the model
right down.

1012
01:08:11,741 --> 01:08:14,741
Difficult to do business with...
on any basis.

1013
01:08:16,946 --> 01:08:19,946
Totally intolerant of
a mistake made by anybody.

1014
01:08:21,317 --> 01:08:24,317
But very instrumental
in starting that company.

1015
01:08:24,954 --> 01:08:27,954
I think that we were difficult
to workwith.

1016
01:08:28,558 --> 01:08:31,558
We were all very independent.
We were used to
having our own way.

1017
01:08:32,328 --> 01:08:35,328
You know,
certainly there's the mind-set
that has to go along...

1018
01:08:35,531 --> 01:08:38,531
with years and years and years
of people saying that, you know,

1019
01:08:39,102 --> 01:08:41,002
"You can't do what
you say you're going to do,"

1020
01:08:41,003 --> 01:08:44,003
"You can't make money'
even if you could do it,"

1021
01:08:44,173 --> 01:08:47,173
um, and that "You're
the wrong person to do it."

1022
01:08:50,913 --> 01:08:53,913
We bought a third of the company
for $2.8 million.

1023
01:08:54,750 --> 01:08:57,750
And we had an agreement
that basically said,

1024
01:08:58,488 --> 01:09:01,189
"You get a third of the company'
and we get a third of the company'

1025
01:09:01,190 --> 01:09:04,190
and we will find the people
to run this company."

1026
01:09:10,133 --> 01:09:12,100
None ofus had ever
built a company.

1027
01:09:12,101 --> 01:09:15,101
We understood that
there was an enormous need for-
for more structure,

1028
01:09:17,773 --> 01:09:20,773
and to bring in people that
we had no way to reach.

1029
01:09:24,180 --> 01:09:27,180
Sandy and Len aggreed to
step down into new roles.

1030
01:09:29,385 --> 01:09:32,287
And Don Valentine
recruited John Morgridge,

1031
01:09:32,288 --> 01:09:35,288
a veteran of several high-tech
start-ups, to run Cisco.

1032
01:09:37,693 --> 01:09:40,693
Morgridge's first task was to address
what he and Don Valentine saw...

1033
01:09:42,198 --> 01:09:44,866
as a troubled corporate culture.

1034
01:09:44,867 --> 01:09:47,867
The quarter that I arrived,
we hired a shrink.

1035
01:09:49,839 --> 01:09:52,839
He eliminated fighting
in the open hallways.

1036
01:09:53,776 --> 01:09:56,776
Physical fighting, I mean.

1037
01:09:57,647 --> 01:10:00,282
I actually had the, uh...

1038
01:10:00,283 --> 01:10:03,283
vice president of engineering deck
the sales vice president in my office!

1039
01:10:09,625 --> 01:10:12,625
We really did have
a trench mentality.

1040
01:10:13,763 --> 01:10:16,763
This is not a good
big-company mentality.
Quelle surprise!

1041
01:10:17,733 --> 01:10:20,001
But, on the other hand,

1042
01:10:20,002 --> 01:10:23,002
I think that
there was no one there
in that original group...

1043
01:10:23,139 --> 01:10:26,139
who didn't ardently
love that company.

1044
01:10:28,678 --> 01:10:31,678
As Cisco grew,
a culture clash developed...

1045
01:10:32,048 --> 01:10:35,048
between the original employees
and the new hires.

1046
01:10:36,018 --> 01:10:39,018
And ultimately, this clash
centered on Sandy Lerner.

1047
01:10:40,590 --> 01:10:43,590
She was definitely
a strong personality,

1048
01:10:43,726 --> 01:10:46,726
and she definitely was the reason
the company existed.

1049
01:10:48,264 --> 01:10:51,264
Sandy was an incredible piece
in the puzzle...

1050
01:10:53,502 --> 01:10:56,502
of getting things done right
for the customer.

1051
01:10:56,772 --> 01:10:59,772
Silicon Valley has not always
been the place where
the customer's thought of first.

1052
01:11:02,912 --> 01:11:05,912
They may, in some places,
be thought of second or third.

1053
01:11:06,115 --> 01:11:09,115
But Sandywas ensuring
that the customer
was thought of first.

1054
01:11:12,588 --> 01:11:15,588
Unfortunately, at the expense
of some of the other
major managers.

1055
01:11:20,363 --> 01:11:23,363
I had very much alienated
the other people in the company,

1056
01:11:25,534 --> 01:11:28,534
because, you know, other than Len,
they hadn't been there very long,

1057
01:11:30,072 --> 01:11:33,072
and, you know, I saw them,
rightly or wrongly,

1058
01:11:34,210 --> 01:11:37,210
as the people I was trying
to protect the customers from.

1059
01:11:38,214 --> 01:11:41,214
By her own admission,
she would detonate.

1060
01:11:42,752 --> 01:11:45,752
Usually in my office.

1061
01:11:46,856 --> 01:11:49,856
At Cisco, you know,
being the only woman
and a technical woman,

1062
01:11:51,227 --> 01:11:53,328
I think I was just very,
very frightening.

1063
01:11:53,329 --> 01:11:56,329
And there just
wasn't a box for me.

1064
01:11:56,332 --> 01:11:59,332
And I think that I didn't make it...

1065
01:11:59,869 --> 01:12:02,869
particularly easy
for them to ignore me.

1066
01:12:03,005 --> 01:12:06,005
And I didn't make it
particularly easy for them
to find a suitable box.

1067
01:12:07,910 --> 01:12:10,578
Um, in that, you know,

1068
01:12:10,579 --> 01:12:13,579
the boxes that existed for women
at the time didn't seem to fit
what I thought I-I was doing.

1069
01:12:20,456 --> 01:12:23,456
Finally one day,

1070
01:12:24,393 --> 01:12:27,393
my assistant said
the conference room is filled...

1071
01:12:30,132 --> 01:12:33,132
with eight Cisco employees
demanding to see you.

1072
01:12:37,039 --> 01:12:40,039
All of the vice presidents
of the company
were in the conference room.

1073
01:12:41,110 --> 01:12:44,110
They walked up Sand Hill Road
and said, "Either she goes, or we go."

1074
01:12:46,315 --> 01:12:49,315
"Terminate her,
or we're quitting.

1075
01:12:49,952 --> 01:12:52,087
All of us."

1076
01:12:52,088 --> 01:12:55,088
And he called me and said, uh,
"Do you want me to handle this?"

1077
01:12:56,058 --> 01:12:58,526
And I said, "No, I'll handle it."

1078
01:12:58,527 --> 01:13:01,527
And Sandy was retired.

1079
01:13:04,367 --> 01:13:07,367
First of all, I mean,
let's just get it out.
I was fired.

1080
01:13:10,573 --> 01:13:13,573
John called me into his office.

1081
01:13:15,378 --> 01:13:18,378
He said, "You know,

1082
01:13:19,215 --> 01:13:20,815
you're now worth
so much money,

1083
01:13:20,816 --> 01:13:23,816
it really doesn't make any sense
foryou to work this hard.

1084
01:13:24,620 --> 01:13:27,620
You know,
I think it's just a good idea...

1085
01:13:28,290 --> 01:13:31,290
if you just, you know,
retire at this point."

1086
01:13:32,762 --> 01:13:35,196
I said, "But, John,
I have a lot to do here.

1087
01:13:35,197 --> 01:13:38,197
I-You know, I think I have
a, you know, a place in-
in the company,

1088
01:13:40,636 --> 01:13:43,338
and I-I-I don't really
want to retire right now."

1089
01:13:43,339 --> 01:13:45,473
I was... 35 years old.

1090
01:13:45,474 --> 01:13:48,474
Um, and he said, "Well,

1091
01:13:48,911 --> 01:13:51,911
I think today's your last day."

1092
01:13:53,382 --> 01:13:56,382
I walked to Len's office'
where Len informed me that
I must surely be mistaken.

1093
01:14:00,556 --> 01:14:03,556
And I sat in Len's office
while Len went up
and talked to John.

1094
01:14:04,059 --> 01:14:07,059
And, uh, came back and
walked out the door with me.

1095
01:14:10,933 --> 01:14:13,933
And we never walked back in.

1096
01:14:18,207 --> 01:14:21,207
You know, this idea that 45 %
of founders will be gone
in 18 months?

1097
01:14:23,412 --> 01:14:26,314
In retrospect,
that was clearly the mind-set.

1098
01:14:26,315 --> 01:14:29,315
Len and I clearly did not understand
that that was the game
that we were playing.

1099
01:14:30,186 --> 01:14:33,186
You know,
the first rule of any game is
to know that you're in one.

1100
01:14:35,157 --> 01:14:38,157
It's an unpleasant thing to do,
to fire anybody.

1101
01:14:39,195 --> 01:14:42,195
But it's clearly the facts of life.

1102
01:14:47,236 --> 01:14:50,236
I think
each of them went away
with 170 million.

1103
01:14:51,640 --> 01:14:54,640
I don't know
how people think of
what comes next...

1104
01:14:54,877 --> 01:14:56,845
after the first 170 million,

1105
01:14:56,846 --> 01:14:59,846
but, uh, I don't think they've
ever forgiven either of us.

1106
01:15:06,088 --> 01:15:09,088
I was once asked,
did I start Cisco to make
a whole bunch of money?

1107
01:15:10,359 --> 01:15:13,359
And I said, "No.
If I measured myself that way'

1108
01:15:13,996 --> 01:15:16,996
I probably couldn't look at myself
in the mirror in the morning."

1109
01:15:17,066 --> 01:15:20,066
Um, I don't.
I think I've been a pretty good
tool-user, and money is a tool.

1110
01:16:12,521 --> 01:16:15,089
You know, technology
keeps evolving,

1111
01:16:15,090 --> 01:16:18,090
and ever since
Leonardo da Vinci,
it's been evolving,

1112
01:16:20,195 --> 01:16:23,195
and it will continue to evolve
through good times and bad times.

1113
01:16:23,666 --> 01:16:26,666
It will evolve.

1114
01:16:27,903 --> 01:16:30,903
Venture capital
is here to stay though.

1115
01:16:41,483 --> 01:16:44,483
Well, I get my greatest
satisfaction out of thinking back
on the companies...

1116
01:16:47,022 --> 01:16:50,022
that I helped start
and helped grow.

1117
01:16:58,701 --> 01:17:01,701
It's... nice to sit in the glow
of your adulation,

1118
01:17:03,372 --> 01:17:06,372
but... without the entrepreneurs,
you're nothing!

1119
01:17:08,344 --> 01:17:11,344
You have to have these
real people with the ideas...

1120
01:17:11,914 --> 01:17:14,515
and their willingness
to commit their life.

1121
01:17:14,516 --> 01:17:16,884
I don't think,
and I would not say...

1122
01:17:16,885 --> 01:17:19,885
that Silicon Valley is the result
of good venture capitalists.

1123
01:17:21,790 --> 01:17:23,191
Not at all.

1124
01:17:23,192 --> 01:17:24,759
Entrepreneurship
is the main show.

1125
01:17:24,760 --> 01:17:27,528
Venture capital is an aid,
and sometimes people got lost-

1126
01:17:27,529 --> 01:17:29,230
"We must have venture capital."

1127
01:17:29,231 --> 01:17:32,231
No use having venture capital
unless you have entrepreneurs.

1128
01:17:32,434 --> 01:17:35,434
If it hadn't been for
the Treybigs and Swansons,

1129
01:17:35,604 --> 01:17:38,604
where would Kleiner and I
have been?

1130
01:17:42,978 --> 01:17:45,978
Without venture capital,
the future wouldn't happen
nearly as quickly.

1131
01:17:48,951 --> 01:17:51,951
New companies are much better
at exploiting new technology.

1132
01:17:52,821 --> 01:17:55,289
